<P>THere are also other cogitati|ons more daungerous, and more importunate then the for|mer: which especially are wont <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">o set vpon those, who first enter <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">nto this way: and they be the co|gitations of infidelity, and blas|phemy. For carnalmen, whose co|gitations &amp; desires are wholy car|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">al, albeit they be conuerted vnto <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">he Lord, yet by &amp; by they cannot <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">orget the figures and similitudes <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">f those things, which they haue <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">eene in the world. For as <HI>Rachell</HI> when she went out of her cou~try
